post_text:
DK Parents,
Now that we've got the first week of school under our belt, we'd like to hear from you on how the week went. The link below is a short survey with just two questions asking what went well and what we can improve on. Please take a moment to speak with your kid(s) to see how the week went for them. We'd like feedback on new procedures, such as our traffic flow, and safety protocols. We'd appreciate the feedback be delivered in this survey rather than in the Comments of this Facebook post.

Some areas of improvement we are aware of and are working diligently to improve, including traffic flow at drop off and getting our online program running, which we're excited to start next week. But it's also important for us to hear from all of you.

Here's the link to give us feedback- https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/6RYBCVM

Thanks for your time and for a wonderful first week of school!
Kyle Corlett, Superintendent

This is a message from the Athletic Department at Delton Kellogg Schools regarding Executive Order 176 and spectator information.

Delton Kellogg will be issuing 2 admission tickets to each participant of an athletic contest. Coaches and game workers are included in the participant group and will be given two admission tickets as well.

The individual game ticket will need to be brought to the contest(s) and turned in at the ticket gate along with the $5.00 admission fee. The admission fee must be exact change as there will be no change given back at any of our ticket gates.

You MUST have an admission ticket to be allowed into the venue.

We will adjust this process as additional Executive Orders dictate. Your cooperation with this process is greatly appreciated.

Thanks and Go Panthers!

Online Learning Update!
Students enrolled for the DK online program should hear from their online teachers soon! The online teachers include:
For grades K-3, the teacher will be Andrea Alkema- Andrea is a new hire (we stole her from Paw Paw) with 15 years of teaching experience!
For grades 3-6, the teacher will be Mark Carlson- Mark and Andrea will split 3rd grade. Mark has taught 5th grade at DKMS since 1995
For grades 7-8, the teacher will be Monique Reed- Monique has taught Math at DKMS since 2008
For grades 9-12, the teacher will be Carla Poignard- Carla has taught English at the high school and served as a media center expert since 2000

Thanks for your patience! These teachers will ensure you have a good experience with our online program

post_text:
Non-homestead Operating Millage Renewal
DKS has arranged for a millage renewal proposal to be on the ballot for the August 4 election. The proposal is to renew the non-homestead millage amount of 18 mills. The approval of the millage renewal proposal is critically important to the Delton Kellogg Schools because it provides for approximately $2.5 million in revenue to operate the schools. This funding is the absolute essential funding we receive from the state. Every year it decreases slightly due to inflation, so about every 4 or 5 years we have to ask voters to renew it back up to 18. The ballot language says that we are asking to increase it by .5 mills, but that is to prevent it from going under 18 by inflation. The most the school can levy is 18 and the state expects us to collect that much. If not, we will see a decrease in funds that we use to operate. Please remember to vote in August!

The most the school can levy is 18 and the state expects us to collect that much. If not, we will see a decrease in funds that we use to operate. Please remember to vote in August!

post_text:
Summer Meal Program Update!
Dear Delton Kellogg Parents,
Delton Meet Up and Eat Up program WILL NOT be available for the Tuesday evening drive thru 4:30-6:30 beginning this Tuesday, July 21st. This is due to the lowered amount of participants.
We WILL be at all morning stops every Tuesday and Friday thru August 18th.
This week on Tuesday July 21st we will have art kits and sketch pads available for parents to take for their children. Friday, July 24th we will have dairy boxes and fruit boxes. These boxes are one per family. These boxes are a USDA program and we appreciate the opportunity to hand these out. Delton Schools has requested additional boxes this week but we will not know our quantity until we receive them.
Thank you for allowing us to continue to offer food to our community and your children. We look forward to seeing you in the Fall.
Sharon Boyle
Delton Kellogg Food Service Department
269-623-1223

The Hastings Banner is with Alex Dayus at Gilmore Car Museum.
>>>>>>> master
July 11 at 12:08 AM · Hickory Corners, MI ·

“As you guys go out and go forward with your lives and make an impact in the world￼ remember this, nobody will ever break the record you guys set for the longest senior skip day in history. Congratulations,” said Gilmore Car Museum curator Jay Follis as he welcomed the Delton Kellogg High School Class of 2020 to its long overdue graduation ceremony Friday.

The ceremony, broadcast to the vehicles of friends and family via radio waves across the museum’s western grounds and broadcast around the world on Facebook, finally honored the 77 members of the Delton Kellogg graduating class who ceased face-to-face learning at school in mid-March because of the global coronavirus pandemic.

Ashton Ingersoll and Sarah Barney shared the class history with their classmates before salutatorian Amber Mabie and valedictorian Erin Kapteyn addressed the crowd. Superintendent Kyle Corlett was the final speaker before the new DK graduates crossed the stage to receive their diplomas, moved their tassels and then flung their mortarboards into the sunny skies.

post_text: We are extremely excited about our upcoming DKHS and DK Academy graduation ceremonies on July 10 at the Gilmore Car Museum! We wanted to let everyone know that due to social distancing guidelines, attendance will be limited to two cars per graduating senior. If you're unable to attend the ceremony, we will be broadcasting it live on Facebook! We have worked hard with the Gilmore Car Museum on making this event be possible, and appreciate everyone's understanding and flexibility that will help us pull this off. We also appreciate the Gilmore's willingness to let us use their beautiful facility. And we can't wait to celebrate our Seniors on July 10th!

This is a message from the Athletic Department at Delton Kellogg Schools regarding upcoming HS volleyball summer conditioning.

Starting Tuesday, June 23rd, there will be voluntary conditioning workouts for all HS volleyball participants. The workouts are scheduled for Tuesdays and Thursdays from 6-7 pm on the HS football practice field. Your student is encouraged to bring their own water and bottles are not to be shared. Student athletes will be separated into Pods during the workout sessions and will remain with those pods throughout the summer workouts per Executive Orders and MHSAA guidelines.

There will be no access to any of the buildings on campus so please be prepared for that when coming to the workouts.

We certainly hope this communication finds you healthy and safe as we venture through this most interesting time. Further updates will be shared as they become available. If you have any questions, please contact the Athletic Office at 269 623-1524.

Thanks and Go Panthers!

post_text:
DK Elementary Technology Collection (Chromebooks & iPads)

Dear DKES Families,

Thank you for those of you that made it to our technology drop off dates last week, however, we still have quite a few Chromebooks and iPads still out. If you have enrolled your child in our virtual summer school then please keep your technology devices until Mid-August.

Collection Times and Dates:

I will be in the office tomorrow (Thursday) from 8:00 AM-12:00 PM (June 11th) and all day on Friday, June 12th (8:00 AM-3:00 PM) for technology drop off.

Please use the main elementary office doors. I will also have yearbooks available for you. If you didn't order one they are on sale for $8.00 each. If these dates and times do not work for you please call my office at 269-623-1535 to schedule a drop off time and date.

Thank you so much for your support with the collection of these devices.

Sincerely,

Mrs. Bourdo

DK Parents,
We've got a couple of important updates for you. The first is a reminder that tomorrow night, Wednesday, April 29, we will be having a meal pick up at DK High School from 4-6 p.m. It will be crazy hat night so please come out and see some of your favorite DKS staff members wearing crazy hats.

Also, for parents of seniors, caps and gowns have been ordered with an expected delivery date of May 15. The high school will set up a time for them to get picked up as we get closer to that date. Please stay tuned for updates about graduation as we'll communicate new info when available.

Kindergarten registration packets are available for pick up in the entryway of the elementary school.…

Michigan is First State to Provide Food to Families Affected
by School Closings Caused by COVID-19

Families with children who received free, reduced-cost lunches at school qualify for new program

LANSING, MICH. Michigan has become the first state in the country to gain federal approval of a program that will provide nutritious food to children who were affected by school closings due to COVID-19.

The Pandemic Electronic Benefit Transfer Program (P-EBT) provides temporary funding to address emergency food needs and avert financial hardship for families affected by the pandemic.

The food assistance benefits will go to Michigan families with students ages…

DK Parents,
This is a reminder that there is a drive thru meal pickup from 4-6 p.m. tonight at Delton Kellogg High School. Our food service has made a special meal that will be easy to pick up and go without leaving the comfort of your own car.

Also, this is also a reminder that new instruction will be beginning April 20th, online or by distributing paper copies of resources to parents. Please stay tuned as each building will be sending out messages soon regarding picking up student Chromebooks if you don't have them yet and information regarding grades.

Thanks for your patience as we work on how to best support students during this time!

UPDATE For DK Parents and Students,

New Instruction- Yesterday's Executive Order by the Governor now allows schools to provide new instruction to students remotely. Previous to this order, we could not provide new instruction to students because of a variety of state requirements that the Governor is now waiving. New instruction will begin on April 20th. Please look for communications by your students' teachers within the next couple of weeks on how this will look. This is new for all of us, so please be patient as teachers figure out the best way to provide new instruction online and remotely. We have amazing teachers and we will be offering training and support for them, but we're sure to… More

DK parents,

Please keep your kids home if they have a fever, are vomiting, have diarrhea, have a chronic cough, have a rash, or have an eye infection.
Remember to keep them home until they are symptom free for at least 24 hours without any medication.
We do our best to keep kids at school, but if they are contagious, we need them to stay home. Please be sure to report any symptoms to the office. Thank you for your help and continued support for being the first line of defense for keeping our students healthy

Delton Kellogg Parents,

At approximately 11:30 a.m. today, all of the buildings at Delton Kellogg Schools went into a soft lockdown. This means that classroom instruction continued but students were brought in from outside and not allowed to leave the classroom. Barry Township Police had pulled someone over in the parking lot of the middle school. At no time were students in danger. Barry Township Police communicated when the lockdown could be lifted. The lockdown lasted for about 5 minutes.

Thank you as always for your support of Delton Kellogg Schools,
Kyle Corlett, Superintendent

Good Luck Panthers!

post_text:
FREE Breakfast For All Students

Delton Kellogg Schools have offered FREE breakfast to all students this school year. This pilot program
has shown an increase of over 10,000 additional breakfasts being served to our students from
September 3, 2019 thru December 20, 2019 over last school year, with a total of over 29,000 breakfast being served.
Our breakfast includes whole grains, fruit and milk. Each day a hot item is offered along with several
cold options. Research has shown that students who eat breakfast average 17.5 higher math test
scores and miss 1.5 less days each school year from being sick.
“No Kid Hungry” starts with breakfast and we are thankful that our administration and Board… More

This is a message from the Athletic Department at Delton Kellogg High School regarding events on Saturday, January 11th, 2020.

The Varsity Swim/Dive Invite at Hastings, the Varsity wrestling invite at West Catholic, the JV wrestling invite at Plainwell and the Varsity Cheer Invite at Gull Lake have all been canceled due to the upcoming weather related issues on Saturday.

These events will not be rescheduled.

If you have any questions, please contact the Athletic Office at 269 623-1524. Thanks and Go Panthers!

ALSO- All follies practices are canceled for Saturday 1-11-2020. Mrs. Broussard will be contacting all participants for future practices.

post_text:
Kristen Perrino, from the American Cancer Society, was presented a check in the amount of $2500.00 by a handful of DK students, and organizer Misty Kapteyn, to be donated towards the fight against cancer. Through t-shirt sales, proceeds donated by our Athletic Boosters from their 50/50 drawing at our Coaches vs Cancer football game, a portion of the Week 9 gate receipts and the Miracle Minute donation sponsored by our DK Cheerleading Team, the DK Community rose up and responded to fighting this disease.
A special Thank You to all who took part and what a Great Day it is to be a Panther!

post_text:
Delton Kellogg's Cross Country Team has enjoyed a bit of success this past week with two of its runners from the boy's team qualifying for the State Meet at MIS this upcoming Saturday and a handful of Harriers earning post season honors.
>>>>>>> master

Matt Lester and Micah Ordway have earned the opportunity to compete at the highest level this weekend at the MHSAA State Meet at Michigan International Speedway in Brooklyn, MI with their performances at this past weekend's Regional Meet at Allendale HS.

The Barry County Meet was held on Monday at Charlton Park and coming home with 1st team All County honors were Matt Lester, Micah Ordway and Halena Phillips. Honorable Mention honors went to Amon Smith, Hector Jimenez, Aubrey Aukerman and Lily Timmerman.

All Conference Honors from the previous week found Matt Lester, Micah Ordway, Amon Smith, Aubrey Aukerman and Halena Phillips earning 1st team SAC selection. Austin Blocker and Dawson Grizzle earned Honorable Mention honors.

Congrats to our boy's and girl's cross country teams and good luck to Matt and Micah on Saturday.
text:
Delton Kellogg's Cross Country Team has enjoyed a bit of success this past week with two of its runners from the boy's team qualifying for the State Meet at MIS this upcoming Saturday and a handful of Harriers earning post season honors.

Matt Lester and Micah Ordway have earned the opportunity to compete at the highest level this weekend at the MHSAA State Meet at Michigan International Speedway in Brooklyn, MI with their performances at this past weekend's Regional Meet at Allendale HS.

The Barry County Meet was held on Monday at Charlton Park and coming home with 1st team All County honors were Matt Lester, Micah Ordway and Halena Phillips. Honorable Mention honors went to Amon Smith, Hector Jimenez, Aubrey Aukerman and Lily Timmerman.

All Conference Honors from the previous week found Matt Lester, Micah Ordway, Amon Smith, Aubrey Aukerman and Halena Phillips earning 1st team SAC selection. Austin Blocker and Dawson Grizzle earned Honorable Mention honors.

Congrats to our boy's and girl's cross country teams and good luck to Matt and Micah on Saturday.

Thank you to everyone for all your support so far this school year. We've had a great start to the year!

Therefore, DK's semifinal match up (10/15) with Holland Christian, originally scheduled for 6:00 pm at Saugatuck HS has been moved to Holland Christian HS with the original start time of 6:00 PM. The originally scheduled 8:00 pm semifinal with Fennville and Maple Valley has been moved up to 6:00 pm at Saugatuck.

The District Finals on Thursday, October 17th will be held at Saugatuck HS with a start time of 6:00 pm. Best of Luck to our Panthers!

From The Food Service Department

Free and Reduced Lunch Applications for 2019-2020
If your child was receiving free or reduced meals last year that benefit carried over into this current school year until October 15, 2019.

October 15, 2019 all students without an application or direct certification from the state on file will be changed to full pay status for lunches. If your student is free based on direct certification from the state you would have received a letter from the Food Service Department by October 1, 2019.

Applications cannot be backdated so please do not wait to submit a new application. Applications can be filled out online at lunchapp.com or are available in all building offices.
If you have any questions please contact me at 269-623-1223 or Amanda Moore at 269-623-1331.

Thank you,
Sharon Boyle
Delton Kellogg Food Service

This is a message from the Athletic Department at Delton Kellogg High School with results from Wednesday's District 34-3 Soccer results.

Delton Kellogg defeated Hopkins 3-1 and have advanced to the semifinal round on Tuesday, October 15th at 5:30 pm vs the winner of the Bloomingdale/Holland Christian winner. The winner of DK's semifinal match will compete in the District Finals on Thursday, October 17th at 7:00 pm, vs the Fennville/Comstock winner. Both semifinals and the final matches will be held at Fennville HS. Congrats to Coach Alan Mabie, Coach Poling and their team for a big tournament win.

The win moves DK's overall record to 10-5-2 on the season. Good Luck Panthers!!

post_text: October is College Month across the State of Michigan. At Delton Kellogg we define college as any post-secondary training, certification, or licensing as well as the more traditional college degrees. We know that in most cases today’s economy will require our graduates to pursue some further training to be ready for the jobs that are available. With that in mind we are working hard to expose our students to a variety of career pathways as they explore their options. We know that not all students are headed to a college campus and with the increased need in the skilled trades we want to help our students see what is possible. On Friday, we took a bus load of students on our first… More

Due to our soccer field being unplayable with the amount of rain we have received over the past 24 hours, we have moved today's soccer match to Kalamazoo Christian HS. The game will still start at 5:00 pm and will be played at KCHS' soccer field on their campus.

Parchment, Comstock and Fennville are on the other side of the bracket.

The Barry-Eaton District Health Department has asked us to send out an update about the mosquito borne virus EEE. The state will be conducting aerial spraying to fight the mosquito virus. The spraying may start as soon as this Sunday evening and includes 14 counties. To find out more about when and where the spraying will occur, as well as more information about EEE, please visit https://www.michigan.gov/emergingdiseases/0,4579,7-186-76711_77442---,00.html

All spraying will be conducted between dusk and dawn. Although they are reporting the spraying is not supposed to be a health risk for humans, you may prefer to avoid being outdoors at that time.

DKS will continue to schedule outdoor…

This Wednesday, (9/25) the XC meet at Galesburg Augusta MS start at 5:00 pm. The JV football game vs Schoolcraft AT DK on Thursday, (9/26) will begin at 5:00 pm. The Varsity football game at Schoolcraft has been moved to Saturday, (9/28) with a 5:00 pm kickoff. Please make a note of these changes to your schedules.

Information regarding next week's events will come out later this week.

As a reminder, the County Health Department has suggested that if you are going to be out of doors during the dawn and dusk periods of the day, to use bug spray with at least 25% DEET and to where long pants and long sleeve shirts as a means of minimizing exposure to the mosquitoes that carry the EEE virus.

This post is for informational purposes. If you have any questions, please contact the Athletic Office at 269 623-1524.

The Gilmore Car Museum hosts a free afterschool program for high school students who want to learn about auto restoration. Students work with mentors in teams and learn skill by actually working on antique autos from the museum. Garage Works meets Tuesday and Thursday from 4 to 7 p.m. at the Garage Works Building at the Gilmore.

The Open House is TONIGHT, Thursday, 12 September, from 5 to 7 p.m. This is a good time for parents and kids to see the program and shop. Also, if they are interested in being in the program this is a good time to sign up.

post_text:
Please consider supporting the Delton Kellogg Education Foundation, which is not affiliated with the school but is a great partner-

Barry County’s KickStart to Career program will open its 5th year of accounts in January 2020. The program was designed to help with post-secondary education expenses whether a student chooses a certification program, trade school, or four-year college.

In the 4th annual Classy campaign there is another chance to invest in the future of Barry County! Through our partnership, with the 1:1 Fund, any donation made Monday, September 9th through Friday, September 13th will be matched dollar for dollar up to $500 per donor.

The money raised, during this campaign, will be added to the incentive fund for Delton Kellogg Students. These fund were created to support each school district's Positive Behavior Intervention and Support (PBIS) program by awarding the chosen student of the month with a deposit into their KickStart account.

To give to the Delton Kellogg KickStart to Career program, please visit https://give.classy.org/kickstartfordk2019

In the 4th annual Classy campaign there is another chance to invest in the future of Barry County! Through our partnership, with the 1:1 Fund, any donation made Monday, September 9th through Friday, September 13th will be matched dollar for dollar up to $500 per donor.

The money raised, during this campaign, will be added to the incentive fund for Delton Kellogg Students. These fund were created to support each school district's Positive Behavior Intervention and Support (PBIS) program by awarding the chosen student of the month with a deposit into their KickStart account.

To give to the Delton Kellogg KickStart to Career program, please visit https://give.classy.org/kickstartfordk2019

DK Community- MDOT has recently installed a crosswalk button that will turn the street light red in front of DK Elementary School. We want everyone to be aware of this change for the safety of our students crossing the street. There is a crossing guard out there at the beginning and end of the school day, but the crosswalk button works at any time of day to stop traffic.

Also, there is extra parking behind the District Library, so elementary parents can park there and cross the street at the crosswalk.

Delton Kellogg Parents with students attend the Battle Creek Math and Science Center,
Transportation for students attending the Battle Creek Math and Science Center will begin August 22nd. Students attending in the morning will have a departure time of 6:45 a.m. from the student parking lot at Delton Kellogg High School. Their return to DKHS will be around 11:30 a.m. Students attending in the afternoon will leave at 10:45 in front of DKHS and will return around 3:20 p.m.

Just a reminder for once the school year starts- if Delton Kellogg Schools has to cancel school for any reason, including inclement weather, transportation for the Battle Creek Math and Science Center will also be cancelled.

This post is for informational purposes only. If you have question, please call the administrative office at 269-623-1501

FREE Breakfast at DKS!

Delton Kellogg Schools will be offering FREE breakfast to all students during the school year 2019-2020. This will be offered as a pilot program. The program will be evaluated at the end of the 2019-2020 school year. All students, regardless of their ability to pay and lunch status will be given a FREE breakfast in each building. Breakfast menus will be posted on the dkschools.org website monthly.

Summer Youth Sports Camps are being scheduled and are as follows:

Girl's basketball will be June 10th-12th from 9:00 am through 11:30 am and girl's volleyball will be June 10th-12th from 1:00-3:30 pm. Camps will be held in the HS gymnasium. Please use the north Aux gym hallway entrance. Lunches will be provided in the HS cafeteria during those three days. (There is a cost savings if registering for both camps)

Boy's and girl's youth Soccer camp will be held June 19th, 20th and 21st at the Varsity soccer field from 9:30-11:30 am.

Information regarding the cost of the camps and registration forms can be picked up in any of the school's offices or found on the school's webpage. Pre-registration is suggested but kids can sign up on the first day of camp as well.

Any questions, please contact the Athletic Office at 269 623-1524. Thanks and Go Panthers!!

The Hastings Banner is at Union City High School.
June 1, 2019 at 7:52 PM · Union City, MI ·

Decisions. Decisions.

The first thought was for a "we're number one" celebration, with a single finger waving aloft.

The second thought was for a two-fingered salute for back-to-back district championships.

The final choice for team photos after the Delton Kellogg varsity softball team captured its second straight Division 3 District Championship was for a three on the right hand and a zero on the left, signifying their 30 wins so far this season.

Delton Kellogg defeated district host Union City 10-0 in six innings in the district championship game Saturday, improving to 30-7 on the season with their two wins on the day.

Baseball and softball will be headed to Union City HS on Saturday, June 1st for their respective District Tournaments. BB will compete against Union City and SB will go up against Bronson. Game time at noon. Winners will move on to the District Finals immediately following those games.

We will be sending three of our boy's track student athletes to the June 1st State Meet at Jenison HS. Cole Pape will compete in the discus (approx. 9:30 am), Nico Dumas in the 100 M Dash (approx. 10:30 am) and Jordan Rench in the 300 IM Hurdles (approx. 2:45 pm).
Best of luck to our three Panthers.

post_text: DK Parents, we understand the change in high school school start time from 7:55 to 7:50 a.m. may be a challenge for some. Our middle school is open to students at 7:30 a.m. and our elementary is open at 7:47 a.m. If anyone needs to drop students off earlier to the elementary for their high school student to report on time, please let administration know by email or telephone for the quickest response, and we will work to fix it. Thank you for your support as we work to meet state requirements for instructional hours without changing everyone's schedules. Change isn't easy, but we're here to help.

post_text: Delton Kellogg High School will be short 4.25 hours this school year. The state requires the district to make up these hours, which are due to early dismissals and late starts from inclement weather. To make up this time, we will be taking two courses of action. First, the 1/2 day scheduled for June 11th will now be a full day of school for the entire district. Second, we will be starting the High School day at 7:50 am (the MS and ES will remain 7:55 am) starting Monday, April 29. This will add 5 minutes onto our school day and make up half of the hours we need to meet the state requirements. The last scheduled day of school is currently June 13. High school exams are planned for June 11, June 12, and June 13.
text: Delton Kellogg High School will be short 4.25 hours this school year. The state requires the district to make up these hours, which are due to early dismissals and late starts from inclement weather. To make up this time, we will be taking two courses of action. First, the 1/2 day scheduled for June 11th will now be a full day of school for the entire district. Second, we will be starting the High School day at 7:50 am (the MS and ES will remain 7:55 am) starting Monday, April 29. This will add 5 minutes onto our school day and make up half of the hours we need to meet the state requirements. The last scheduled day of school is currently June 13. High school exams are planned for June 11, June 12, and June 13.

Once again, the Delton Kellogg Athletic Department has joined up with Dr Roth, and his office staff, to offer sport's physicals to our student athletes that are entering the 6th through the 12th grades in the 2019-20 school year.
Cost of the physicals will be $10 cash (please, no checks) and will be good for the remainder of this school year and the entire 2019-20 school year.
Physical Day at DK will be held on Wednesday, May 1st from 3-4:30 in the lower level gym hallway in the HS. (Please note: those teams that have an athletic event that day will start their physicals at 2:00 pm)
If you have any questions, please contact the Athletic Office at (269) 623-1524. Thanks and Go Panthers!!

post_text:
Looking to the future of Delton Kellogg Schools, the Board of Education is asking voters to consider a bond proposal on Tuesday, May 7, 2019.
If approved, there would be no expected tax rate increase to property owners, providing phased improvements to Delton Kellogg Schools.
This bond proposal would generate $23,215,000 for district-wide improvements to address identified and ongoing facility and instructional environment needs. The funding would be spent in phases over 10 years to address capital improvements, as a part of the district’s long-term master plan for school buildings and sites.
This bond proposal has three key areas of focus: building and site improvements, educational technology, and district-wide improvements.
Learn more about the May 7, 2019 bond proposal by visiting the district website.
http://dkschools.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/DeltonKellogg_May2019BondProposal_FactSheet_Final-1.pdf

This informational material is paid for by Delton Kellogg Schools, 327 N. Grove St., Delton, MI 49046.

Congratulations to the DK Varsity and Quiz Bowl teams.

The Varsity Team of Joe Gherardi, Hannah Austin, Henrik Wetterdahl, Slater Stanton, Jon Gherardi and Brady Haas tied for First Place with Saugatuck in the Middle Season SAC Tournament last night with a final score of 330.

The JV Team of Evelyn Zettlemaier, Owen Harig, Marco Hickerson, Jacob Shorey, Billy Null took first place with a score of 330.

Congratulations to both teams. This currently places both teams in first place in the SAC Conference for Quiz Bowl competition.

Next meet is at Watervliet High School on March 6 at 4:30 pm.

Just a quick reminder from the Delton Kellogg Athletic Department regarding tonight's (2-8-19) varsity doubleheader at Constantine HS. The start times for those two games are 5:00 pm (girls) and 6:30 pm (boys).

Constantine HS is hosting the Individual Wrestling Districts (of which our Panthers are involved) on Saturday and need to begin preparations for that meet after the basketball games on Friday night and had asked to move the hoop games up an hour.

The Comp Cheer event scheduled for tonight (2/8) at Caledonia High School has been rescheduled for Monday, February 11th at 6:00 pm for the JV team. The varsity team will be attending the previously scheduled Gull Lake Invite on Monday.

Please make a note on your schedules.

If you have any questions, please contact the Athletic Office at 269 623-1524.

Thanks and Go Panthers!!
